sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Remote Access Tool - AnyDesk Execution With Known Revoked Signing Certificate
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the execution of an AnyDesk binary with a version prior to 8.0.8.
Prior to version 8.0.8, the Anydesk application used a signing certificate that got compromised by threat actors.
Use this rule to detect instances of older versions of Anydesk using the compromised certificate
This is recommended in order to avoid attackers leveraging the certificate and signing their binaries to bypass detections.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Sai Prashanth Pulisetti, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
The code creates a directory named "C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk" and downloads the file "AnyDesk.exe" from the URL "http://download.anydesk.com/AnyDesk.exe" to the file path "C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe". 

It then executes the following commands:
- cmd.exe /c C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe --install C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk --start-with-win --silent
- cmd.exe /c echo J9kzQ2Y0qO | C:\ProgramData\anydesk.exe --set-password
- cmd.exe /c C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe --get-id

The first command installs AnyDesk in silent mode with the --start-with-win flag, which starts AnyDesk with Windows. The second command sets the password for AnyDesk to "J9kzQ2Y0qO". The third command gets the AnyDesk ID.

The code defines a PowerShell function named "AnyDesk". The function performs the following actions:

1. Creates a directory at "C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk".
2. Downloads the AnyDesk application from "http://download.anydesk.com/AnyDesk.exe" and saves it as "C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe".
3. Executes the command "cmd.exe /c C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe --install C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk --start-with-win --silent", which appears to install AnyDesk silently and configure it to start with Windows.
4. Executes the command "cmd.exe /c echo J9kzQ2Y0qO | C:\ProgramData\anydesk.exe --set-password", which sets a password for AnyDesk.
5. Executes the command "cmd.exe /c C:\ProgramData\AnyDesk.exe --get-id", which retrieves the ID of the AnyDesk installation.

While the code itself does not contain any obvious malicious behavior, it performs actions that could potentially be used for unauthorized remote access or other malicious activities. The download and execution of an external executable raises concerns about the source and integrity of the downloaded file. Additionally, setting a password and retrieving the ID of the installation may indicate an attempt to gain unauthorized access to systems.

It is important to note that without further context or understanding of the purpose and intent behind this code, it is difficult to definitively classify it as either malicious or benign. However, the combination of these actions raises suspicion and warrants further investigation.
